SingleR cell type exploration - Combining references

Results for SCPCL000296.

This notebook is focused on a preliminary analysis of using SingleR with combining references. I mostly followed the setup outlined in the SingleR book section on combining multiple references with harmonizing labels. To do this, I created a list of all references and then grabbed the label.ont from all references and provided both of those as input to SingleR::SingleR() to annotate a single library.

Set Up

suppressPackageStartupMessages({
  library(SingleCellExperiment)
  library(ggplot2)
})
theme_set(theme_bw())
# make local data directory if it doesn't exist
fs::dir_create(params$local_data_dir)
fs::dir_create(params$local_ref_dir)
# Define list of reference files that we will use for combined analysis
refs <- c("BlueprintEncodeData", 
          "HumanPrimaryCellAtlasData",
          "DatabaseImmuneCellExpressionData",
          "MonacoImmuneData")
ref_files <- glue::glue("celldex-{refs}.rds")
local_ref_paths <- file.path(params$local_ref_dir, ref_files) |>
  purrr::set_names(refs)

# if missing the reference files, grab them from S3
if(!all(file.exists(local_ref_paths))){
  # sync reference files 
  aws_includes <- paste("--include '", ref_files, "'", sep = '', collapse = ' ')
  sync_call <- paste('aws s3 cp', params$s3_ref_dir, params$local_ref_dir,
                     '--exclude "*"', aws_includes,'--recursive', sep = " ")
  system(sync_call, ignore.stdout = TRUE) 
}

# read all ref files in as a single list
celldex_refs <- purrr::map(local_ref_paths, readr::read_rds)
# build path to annotated sce file 
annotated_sce_file <- glue::glue("{params$library_id}_annotated.rds")
local_annotated_sce_path <- file.path(params$local_data_dir, 
                                      params$sample_id, 
                                      annotated_sce_file)

# if missing the annotated sce files, grab them from S3
if(!all(file.exists(local_annotated_sce_path))){
  # sync annotated SCE files 
  aws_includes <- glue::glue('--include "*/{annotated_sce_file}"')
  
  sync_call <- glue::glue('aws s3 sync {params$s3_data_dir} {params$local_data_dir} --exclude "*" {aws_includes}')
  system(sync_call, ignore.stdout = TRUE) 
}

# read in all annotated sce 
annotated_sce <- readr::read_rds(local_annotated_sce_path)

SingleR with combined reference

Before providing the list of references and labels, first subset them so that they contain the same set of genes.

# identify shared genes among all references
shared_ref_genes <- celldex_refs |>
    purrr::map(rownames) |>
    purrr::reduce(intersect)

# create list of refs with shared genes only 
celldex_refs_shared <- celldex_refs |>
  purrr::map(\(ref)
             ref <- ref[shared_ref_genes ,])
# create list of labels 
ont_labels <- celldex_refs_shared |> 
  purrr::map(\(ref) ref$label.ont)
# perform SingleR using combined refs and labels
combined_result <- SingleR::SingleR(test = annotated_sce, 
                                    ref = celldex_refs_shared,
                                    labels = ont_labels)

Evaluate combined reference annotations

Before evaluating some of the output, I wanted to be able to interpret the ontology ID’s so the first thing I did was map the label.ont back to the main labels from each reference then combine that with the SingleR results.

# for each reference, provide a map between ont labels and other labels in the dataset
ref_labels <- celldex_refs_shared |>
  purrr::map(\(ref) data.frame(label_ont = ref$label.ont,
                               label_main = ref$label.main,
                               label_fine = ref$label.fine)) |>
  dplyr::bind_rows(.id = "label_reference")

# add main and fine labels to combined results 
result_df <- combined_result |>
  as.data.frame() |>
  # first recode the reference assigned 
  dplyr::mutate(reference = dplyr::case_when(reference == 1 ~ "BlueprintEncodeData", 
                                             reference == 2 ~ "HumanPrimaryCellAtlasData",
                                             reference == 3 ~ "DatabaseImmuneCellExpressionData",
                                             reference == 4 ~ "MonacoImmuneData")) |>
  # then combine with labels to get main and fine labels associated with ont labels for each reference
  dplyr::left_join(ref_labels, by = c("pruned.labels" = "label_ont", "reference" = "label_reference"))

The first thing I looked at was the labels that end up getting assigned and which reference was used to assign those labels.

# get a tally of the assigned labels and the associated reference
label_counts_df <- result_df |>
  dplyr::count(label_main, reference)

# barchart of labels that are assigned and reference they came from
ggplot(label_counts_df, aes(x = reference, fill = label_main, y = n)) +
  geom_bar(position = "stack", stat = "identity") +
  labs(x = "",
       y = "Number of cells",
       label = "Cell type") +
  guides(x = guide_axis(angle = 90))

# only pull out the top 10 labels 
top_label_counts_df <- result_df |>
  dplyr::mutate(top_labels = forcats::fct_lump_n(label_main, 10)) |>
  dplyr::count(top_labels, reference)

# same barchart but with just the top 10 labels
ggplot(top_label_counts_df, aes(x = reference, fill = top_labels, y = n)) +
  geom_bar(position = "stack", stat = "identity") +
  labs(x = "",
       y = "Number of cells",
       label = "Cell type") +
  guides(x = guide_axis(angle = 90))

It looks like most of the labels are coming from the HSC’s in BlueprintEncodeData reference with a few cells being assigned to other labels present in the other datasets.

Below, I looked at how the labels looked when using all references vs. single references. When running SingleR with multiple references, first DE genes are identified within each reference and labels assigned within each reference and then statistics are merged across references (I’m still slightly unclear on exactly what that means).

# get all the labels from combined and each individual reference
all_results <- result_df |> 
  dplyr::select(ends_with("pruned.labels")) |>
  tidyr::pivot_longer(cols = everything(), 
                      values_to = "label.ont",
                      names_to = "reference") |> 
  # rename final assigned labels as combined and remove some extra strings
  dplyr::mutate(reference = ifelse(reference == "pruned.labels", "combined", reference),
                reference = stringr::str_remove_all(reference, "orig.results.|.pruned.labels")) |>
  # grab top 10 and relevel for ordering
  dplyr::mutate(top_labels = forcats::fct_lump_n(label.ont, 10), 
                reference = factor(reference, 
                                   levels = c("combined", 
                                              "BlueprintEncodeData", 
                                              "HumanPrimaryCellAtlasData",
                                              "DatabaseImmuneCellExpressionData",
                                              "MonacoImmuneData"))) |>
  dplyr::count(top_labels, reference)

# create a barchart to look at assignments between combined vs. single refs 
ggplot(all_results, aes(x = reference, fill = top_labels, y = n)) +
  geom_bar(position = "stack", stat = "identity")  +
  labs(x = "",
       y = "Number of cells",
       label = "Cell type") +
  guides(x = guide_axis(angle = 90))

It looks like the combined references look the most similar to the BlueprintEncodeData as with most cells being labeled as HSCs(CL:0000557) as noted earlier. However, if we used individual references we see that the other references that don’t have HSC’s assign cells as CD34+ progenitors (CL:0002043) or monocytes (CL:0002057). In the combined reference we also see a small portion of the cells are annotated as CD34+ HSCs, which would not have been the case if we only used BlueprintEncodeData.

# make some heatmaps because why not
SingleR::plotScoreHeatmap(combined_result)
